1 Prelinimaries

compute_power <- function(ncp, alpha = 0.05, df = 1, lower = FALSE)
{
  q_alpha <- qchisq(alpha, df = df, lower = lower)
  
  power <- pchisq(q_alpha, df = df, ncp = ncp, lower = lower)
}

2 Parameters

M <- 5e2 # the number of SNPs
N <- as.integer(c(1e2, 5e2, 1e3, 2e3)) # the number of individuals
p <- 0.3 # the MAF of SNPs
f <- 0.5 # the frequency of binary exposure
betaG <- 0.1 # the effect size (simulations on the main genetic effect)

var_explained <- 0.6 # the variance explained by polygenic effect (h2)

ibetaG <- 0.1 # the marginal genetic effect size (GxE simulations)
ibetaE <- 0.1 # the marginal environmental effect size
ibetaGE <- 0.1 # the interaction effect size

3 Analytical formulas

We state that the difference between two NCPs (for GWAS analysis) for unrelated and genetically related designs is by trace factor:

  • testing main genetic (marginal) effect: \(trace(\hat{V}^{-1}K) / N\);
  • testing interaction GxE effect: \(trace(\hat{V}^{-1}K_D) / N\),
    • where \(K_d\) is the element-wise product of \(K\) and \(D\) matrices (\(D\) matrix encodes whether two individuals belong to the same exposure strata when the exposure is binary) (Sul 2016).

3.1 Errata

In the PGSG Seminars talk, we erroneously stated:

\(\Sigma_{x_{ge}} = \sigma^2_{x_g} K \sigma^2_{x_e} I = \sigma^2_{x_g} \sigma^2_{x_e} I\)

It should have been:

\(\Sigma_{x_{ge}} = \sigma^2_{x_g} K \sigma^2_{x_e} D = \sigma^2_{x_g} \sigma^2_{x_e} K_D\)

3.2 Marginal genetic effect

Study Model Genotype \(x_g\) Std. Error (\(\hat{\beta_g}\)) Approximation
Unrelated \(y \sim (\mu + \beta_g g, \sigma_r^2 I)\) \(x_g \sim (pq, 2pq I)\) \(\frac{\sigma_r^2}{x_g^T x_g}\) \(\frac{\sigma_r^2}{2pq N} \approx \frac{1}{2pq N}\)
Genetically related \(y \sim (\mu + \beta_g g, \sigma_g^2 K + \sigma_r^2 I)\) \(x_g \sim (pq, 2pq K)\) \(\frac{{\sigma_r^*}^2}{x_g^T \hat{V}^{-1} x_g}\) \(\frac{{\sigma_r^*}^2}{2pq \mbox{ } trace(\hat{V}^{-1}K)} \approx \frac{1}{2pq \mbox{ } trace(\hat{V}^{-1}K)}\)

Notes

  • \(x_g\) is centered in the formula for Std. Error (\(\hat{\beta_g}\))

3.2.1 Case of sib-pairs

We previously derived here:

\(trace(V^{-1}K) = trace([\sigma_g^2 I + \sigma_r^2 K^{-1}]^{-1}) = \frac{N}{s} (\frac{1}{\sigma_g^2 + 2 \sigma_r^2 / (1 + s)} + \frac{s-1}{\sigma_g^2 + 2 \sigma_r^2})\)

  • \(s\) is the number of siblings per family
  • \(N\) is the total number of individuals
  • \(N/s\) is the number of families

3.3 Interaction GxE effect

Study Model Variable \(x_{ge}\) Std. Error (\(\hat{\beta_g}\)) Approximation
Unrelated \(y \sim (\mu + \beta_g x_g + \beta_e x_e + \beta_{ge} x_{ge}, \sigma_r^2 I)\) \(x_{ge} \sim (pq, 2pq I)\) \(\frac{\sigma_r^2}{x_{ge}^T x_{ge}}\) \(\frac{\sigma_r^2}{2pq N} \approx \frac{1}{2pq N}\)
Genetically related \(y \sim (\mu + \beta_g x_g + \beta_e x_e + \beta_{ge} x_{ge}, \sigma_r^2 I)\) \(x_{ge} \sim (pq, 2pq K_D)\) \(\frac{{\sigma_r^*}^2}{x_{ge}^T \hat{V}^{-1} x_{ge}}\) \(\frac{{\sigma_r^*}^2}{2pq \mbox{ } trace(\hat{V}^{-1}K_D)} \approx \frac{1}{2pq \mbox{ } trace(\hat{V}^{-1}K_D)}\)

Notes

  • \(x_g\) and \(x_e\) are assumed to be independent.
  • Given the independence between \(x_g\) and \(x_e\), the effects sizes \(\beta_g\), \(\beta_e\) and \(\beta_{ge}\) are also independent if:
    • \(x_g\) and \(x_e\) are centered
    • \(x_{ge}\) is derived by element-wise multiplication of centered \(x_g\) and \(x_e\)

4 Marginal genetic effect

4.1 Unrelated

Study Model Genotype \(x_g\) Variance of \(\hat{\beta_g}\) Approximation
Unrelated \(y \sim (\mu + \beta_g g, \sigma_r^2 I)\) \(x_g \sim (pq, 2pq I)\) \(\frac{\sigma_r^2}{x_g^T x_g}\) \(\frac{\sigma_r^2}{2pq N}\) 
out <- lapply(N, function(n) {
  par <- gxefam_par(num_fam = n / 5, sim_gen = "rbinom", sim_phen = "no_rand",
    freq_g  = p)

  dat <- gxefam_sim_dat(par, n = M, beta = c(betaG, 0, 0))

  assoc <- with(dat, matreg(Y = Y, X = G))

  mutate(assoc$tab,
    N = as.integer(n), sim = "unrel")
})
tab1 <- bind_rows(out)
tab1_expected <- data_frame(N = N, beta = betaG, sigma2 = 1) %>%
  mutate(
    se = 1 / sqrt(2 * p * (1 - p) * N),
    ncp = (beta / se)^2,
    power = compute_power(ncp))
    
tab1_power <- group_by(tab1, N) %>% summarize(power = mean(pval < 0.05))

4.2 Genetically related

out <- lapply(N, function(n) {
  par <- gxefam_par(num_fam = n / 5, sim_gen = "rbinom_fam", 
    sim_phen = "gen", var_explained = var_explained,
    freq_g = p)

  dat <- gxefam_sim_dat(par, n = M, beta = c(betaG, 0, 0))

  assoc <- with(dat, matreg(Y = Y, X = G, varcov = varcov))

  list(
    par = par, 
    tab = mutate(assoc$tab,
      N = as.integer(n), sim = "rel_gen"))
})
tab2 <- lapply(out, function(x) x$tab) %>% bind_rows
tab2_expected <- data_frame(N = N, beta = betaG, sigma2 = 1) %>%
  mutate(
    trace_factor = sapply(out, function(x) gxefam_trace_factor(x$par, mult = "K")),
    se = 1 / (sqrt(2 * p * (1 - p) * N) * trace_factor),
    ncp = (beta / se)^2,
    power = compute_power(ncp))
    
tab2_power <- group_by(tab2, N) %>% summarize(power = mean(pval < 0.05))
tab2_expected

5 Interaction GxE effect

5.1 Unrelated

out <- lapply(N, function(n) {
  par <- gxefam_par(num_fam = n / 5, sim_gen = "rbinom", sim_phen = "no_rand",
    freq_g  = p, freq_e = f)

  dat <- gxefam_sim_dat(par, n = M, center = TRUE, beta = c(ibetaG, ibetaE, ibetaGE))

  assoc <- with(dat, matreg(Y = Y, X = GE, Xlist = list(G, E)))

  mutate(assoc$tab,
    N = as.integer(n), sim = "unrel")
})
tab3 <- bind_rows(out)
tab3_expected <- data_frame(N = N, beta = ibetaGE, sigma2 = 1) %>%
  mutate(
    se = 1 / sqrt(2 * p * (1 - p) * f * (1 - f) * N),
    ncp = (beta / se)^2,
    power = compute_power(ncp))

tab3_power <- group_by(tab3, N) %>% summarize(power = mean(pval < 0.05))

5.3 Comparison between unrelated and related (simulations)

6 Conclusions

  • The trace factor depends on the structure of related individuals.
    • Does not depend on the sample size if the nuclear families are the same.
  • The trace factor in the GxE interaction analysis:
    • the influence of the frequency of exposure \(f\)
    • the distribution of exposure within and across nuclear families
    • need to derive the analytical formula for sib-pairs

6.1 Trace factor matters

Analysis Trace factor Gen. related more powerful (trace factor > 1)
Main genetic effect 0.83 no
Interaction GxE effect 1.02 yes
